How to Run on Linux
This core framework runs natively on any modern Linux distribution (Ubuntu, Debian, CentOS, Fedora, etc.) using the built-in Python 3 engine.
### Step 1: Clone the Repository
Open your terminal and pull down the source code:
```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPOSITORY_NAME.git
cd YOUR_REPOSITORY_NAME

```
### Step 2: Verify Python Environment
Ensure your Linux environment has Python 3.8 or higher installed:
```bash
python3 --version

```
*If Python 3 isn't installed, fetch it via your package manager (e.g., sudo apt install python3 on Debian/Ubuntu).*
### Step 3: Set Executable Permissions (Optional)
If you want to run the script cleanly as a standalone binary utility without explicitly typing python3 every time, grant it execution permissions:
```bash
chmod +x mtd_core.py

```
### Step 4: Execute the Simulation
Run the asynchronous defense simulation engine directly from your shell:
```bash
python3 mtd_core.py

```
*(Or ./mtd_core.py if you completed Step 3).*
## ⚙️ Running as a Persistent Background Service (Systemd)
In a live Linux environment, you wouldn't run a security script manually inside an active terminal session. To run this framework as a persistent background daemon that automatically restarts if the server reboots, configure a **Systemd Service Unit**:
 1. Create a new service configuration file:
   ```bash
   sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/mtd-core.service
   
   ```
 2. Paste the following production unit configuration:
```ini
   [Unit]
   Description=Ephemeral MTD Core Shifting Defense Service
   After=network.target

   [Service]
   Type=simple
   User=nobody
   Group=nogroup
   WorkingDirectory=/absolute/path/to/YOUR_REPOSITORY_NAME
   ExecStart=/usr/bin/python3 /absolute/path/to/YOUR_REPOSITORY_NAME/mtd_core.py
   Restart=always
   RestartSec=5

   [Install]
   WantedBy=multi-user.target

```
*(Make sure to replace /absolute/path/to/ with the actual path where your script lives).*
 3. Reload systemd, enable the service to start at boot, and fire it up:
```bash
   sudo systemctl daemon-reload
   sudo systemctl enable mtd-core.service
   sudo systemctl start mtd-core.service

```
 4. Monitor the live security logs natively using journalctl:
   ```bash
   sudo journalctl -u mtd-core.service -f
   
   ```
